  "local_port": 36470,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Is there a database of retail grocery prices?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several databases and resources available that track retail grocery prices. Here are a few notable ones:\n\n1. **Bureau of Labor Statistics (BLS) - Consumer Price Index (CPI):**\n   - The BLS collects data on the prices of food and beverages as part of the CPI. This data is available through their website and can be broken down by various categories and regions.\n   - [BLS CPI Data](https://www.bls.gov/cpi/data.htm)\n\n2. **USDA Economic Research Service (ERS):**\n   - The USDA ERS provides data on food prices, including the Food Price Outlook and the Food Environment Atlas, which offer insights into grocery prices and related economic factors.\n   - [USDA ERS Food Prices](https://www.ers.usda.gov/data-products/food-price-outlook/)\n\n3. **NielsenIQ (formerly Nielsen):**\n   - NielsenIQ provides comprehensive data on retail prices, including groceries. This data is often used by businesses and researchers but typically requires a subscription.\n   - [NielsenIQ](https://nielseniq.com/)\n\n4. **IRI (Information Resources, Inc.):**\n   - IRI offers similar services to NielsenIQ, providing detailed data on consumer goods, including grocery prices. Access usually requires a subscription.\n   - [IRI](https://www.iriworldwide.com/en-us)\n\n5. **Numbeo:**\n   - Numbeo is a crowd-sourced global database that includes grocery prices for various cities around the world. It's freely accessible and useful for getting a general sense of price levels.\n   - [Numbeo Grocery Prices](https://www.numbeo.com/food-prices/)\n\n6. **Local and Regional Government Data:**\n   - Some local and regional governments collect and publish data on grocery prices, especially in areas focused on food security and affordability.\n\nEach of these resources has its own methodology and scope, so the choice of database might depend on the specific needs of your research or project.",
